There were two kinds of pores in the selective layer of the prepared membranes, one is the cavity of β-CD itself, the other is the free volume among polyester chains. Furthermore, the GQDs was effectively incorporated into polyester layer by IP process. The interspace between β-CD and GQDs could cause the void volume which further improved the porosity thereby enhanced the permeability, as shown in Fig. 4. Fig. 5
                        (a) showed that pore width distribution of β-CD NF membrane (0#) and β-CD/GQDs-0.3 NF membrane (3#) calculated by DFT model. The sharp peaks appeared near the pore size of 1.7 and 2.7 nm, respectively, indicating the pores of β-CD and β-CD/GQDs-0.3 NF membranes are distributed in this range. The cavity of β-CD could be presented in HK model (Fig. S7 (c)). The diameter of dye molecular (Congo Red and Alcian Blue) is about 2.0 nm [45] and the rejection of 0# and 3# membrane could reach 90.0% (Fig. 6
                        ). Compared to the experimental results, the pore diameter of the membranes tested by BET is slightly bigger, which was attributed to the bigger pores of the porous PES support formed by phase separation. Meanwhile, molecular weight cutoff (MWCO) of the membranes was estimated by various dyes with different molecular weight, which follows the trend of 0# membrane (760 Da) < 1# membrane (800 Da) < 3# membrane (860 Da), as shown in Fig. 5(b). This could be explained by that the introduction of GQDs effectively changed the surface properties and interface structure of the membrane. It could be concluded that the pore size range essentially kept unchanged even adding GQDs, which further proved that GQDs was completely dispersed and incorporated into selective layer and made it more loose. A filtration test was conducted to separate two mixed dyes by β-CD/GQDs NF membrane, which showed that the cavities of β-CD have been used as effective pores for separations (Fig. S8).
